<div xmlns:java="http://xml.apache.org/xslt/java" id="centre_col"><!-- begin original content --><h1>ESSUM37800 - Approval of schemes:
Retrospective amendments</h1>
<br>
<p>HMRC cannot approve an alteration to a scheme which purports to
have retrospective effect (i.e. expressed to take effect from a
date earlier than it was made) unless the retrospection is
specifically permitted by statute.
<br>
<br> Most requests for approval of retrospective amendments are
concerned with altering scheme rules which set out the framework
within which the scheme is to operate (e.g. scheme limits, window
periods). Amendments which affect the terms of options granted
under the scheme are not normally retrospective amendments (i.e.
expressed to take effect from a date earlier than it was made), and
usually only take effect from the date the amendment is made. For
Guidance on amendments made to a scheme to alter the terms of
existing options see below.
<br>
<br> Companies may seek to amend the terms of an approved SAYE
share option scheme with retrospective effect using a legal process
known as "rectification". But in practice this is likely to be
extremely rare, for two main reasons:</p>
<br>
<ul>
<li class="filledcircle">rectification does not have retrospective
effect unless it has been carried out by the Courts</li>
<li class="filledcircle">the Courts will require proof, to a high
standard, that there was a genuine mistake in the original
document, in the sense that the document does not say what the
parties intended it to say. This is not the same as realising
subsequently that a different form of words would be better for
them.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Amendments affecting existing options</h3>
<p>In share option schemes, unless expressed otherwise, amendments
made to scheme rules will generally be intended to apply:</p>
<br>
<ul>
<li class="filledcircle">from the date of the amendment,</li>
<li class="filledcircle">to options granted in the future and to
options already in existence.</li>
</ul>
<p>If amendments are to apply to existing options, as well as to
new options, before approving the amendment under paragraph 43 it
is necessary to consider</p>
<br>
<ul>
<li class="filledcircle">not just whether the scheme rules will
continue to satisfy the "relevant requirements" of paragraph 1 for
new options granted in accordance with them, but also</li>
<li class="filledcircle">whether the rights conferred by existing
options, as amended, will continue to do so (see below).</li>
</ul>
<p>For SAYE share option schemes the main "relevant requirements"
which may not be satisfied if the terms of existing options are
altered, are those which set conditions which must be satisfied at
the time a "right to acquire shares" is obtained. In particular, at
the time any rights to acquire shares are obtained</p>
<br>
<ul>
<li class="filledcircle">the option-holder must be a director or
employee of a constituent company - paragraph 10</li>
<li class="filledcircle">there is a requirement to enter a linked
savings arrangement - paragraph 24 (see 
<a href="ESSUM34120.htm">ESSUM34120</a>)</li>
<li class="filledcircle">the exercise price must not be manifestly
less than 80% of the market value of the shares at that time (or
any earlier time agreed by the Board) - paragraph 28.</li>
</ul>
<p>References in ESSUM to obtaining &ldquo;rights&rdquo; are to
rights, conferred by share options, to acquire a specified number
of shares, at a specified price, within a specified time. But this
does not necessarily mean that all rights are obtained when the
options (which confer those rights) are granted. It is possible for
an option to confer rights which are obtained after the date the
option is granted. In CIR v Eurocopy plc (see 
<a href="ESSUM47955.htm">ESSUM47955</a>) such rights were obtained
when the terms of the existing options were altered.
<br>
<br> When considering amendments which alter the terms of
existing options, scheme advisors should test whether the amendment
to the scheme submitted for approval would cause existing
option-holders to obtain rights</p>
<br>
<ul>
<li class="filledcircle">which they did not have before the
amendment was made (see 
<a href="ESSUM30220.htm">ESSUM30220</a>),</li>
</ul>
<blockquote>
<blockquote>and</blockquote>
</blockquote>
<ul>
<li class="filledcircle">which would not satisfy all of the
relevant statutory requirements - for example, the market value
requirements relating to the option exercise price in paragraph 28
(see 
<a href="ESSUM35105.htm">ESSUM35105</a>).</li>
</ul>
<h3>New &amp; Old options</h3>
<p>There are occasions where proposed alterations may be capable of
approval; however, as they would change the rights of subsisting
option holders, they can only be approved in respect of options
granted subsequent to the alterations becoming approved and coming
into effect. In these circumstances the approval letter must make
clear that the proposed alterations will only apply to future
grants of options, the scheme rules should clearly distinguish
between &ldquo;new&rdquo; and &ldquo;old&rdquo; options in these

circumstances.</p>
<br>
